How to create a shapefile with beg/end Log mile for a interstate?

Foundamental files¶

  • roadway shapefile i.e., Statewide_Road_geometrics_data.shp, contains route number, name.
  • county shapefile, i.e., TN_count.shp, used for cut routes into multiple parts.

Step 1 Prepare Interstate segments (Note: multple polylines)¶

  • Select segments of a interstate from a roadway shapefile (e.g., DOT roadway shapefile).

  • Save selected segments of a specific interstate, name it as "step1RouteSelection.shp"

  • example:

  1. select target corridor \

  2. right-click the layer "Statewide_Roadway_Geometry" and go to selection, and create layer from selected layers (I_24_segments).

  3. Let's save this layer (export->data) to folder "I_24_raw"

Step 2 Dissolve segments¶

  • **Dissolve** selected segments using shape file "step1RouteSelection.shp"
  • Save dissolved layer as "step2RouteDissolve.shp"

  • The purpose of dissolving segments is to unite all segments into a single route (a polyline)

  • Example \

  • Save new layer as "I_24_dissolve" and export the layer to folder "I_24_dissolve"

Step 3 Cut route by county¶

  • Intersect route (polyline) with county (polygon)

  • Select line as output

  • Example, input file "I_24_dissolve" and "tncounty"

  • Save the new layer as "I_24_cut_by_county" and save it to folder "I_24_cut_by_county"

Step 4 Check the corridor within county

  • This step is to make sure the corridor length is close to (or equal to) the length of report. To do this, we can compare the end of log mile
  • Before we check the route length, let's see if we have following layers.

  • Then, add a new field for layer "I_24_cut_by_county" for the convenience of checking the corridor length

  • Attention**

  • the check may mainly focus on counties where highway traverse in and out more than twice.
  • if not sure about the primary or minor direction, please check raw statewide roadway shapefile.
  • if such case happened, as below figure shows, we need to add an additional column called sequence which is in complinace with CntySeq in pothole dataset. Correspondingly, we have 1, 2 etc.,

  • Figure

  • after adding "sequence" column, we need to split multipart polylines, note that the corridor cut by the county polygon could have multiparts, as above figure shows, it contains two parts. Therefore, before we adding CntySeq, we need to split mulitparts. Herein, we use **Explode** in advanced editing.

  • Note, when style="color:red">**Explode** is used, we may need to merge some of them, if needed, under Editor menus, go to merge after choosing multi-segments.

Specifically, we need to right-click the blank area of the arcmap GUI. Go to check on Advanced Editing. Then go to editor menor, select polyline and start editing. The key functionalitys are shown in below figure.

Add new column "sequence", Meanwhile, update the length "len" if needed.

After check, we should have following information, especially added len. sequence, Cty_code

Generate points along lines (e.g., every 0.1 miles)¶

  • Examples

Save the new layer as "I_24_points_at_line" and save it to folder 'I_24_points_at_line'

Important step¶

Now we are stepping into a very important step. That is, we want to split lines at points while preserving the order of segments.Here's the solution i found in web split_line_at_points

  1. dissolve the segments ("I_24_cut_by_county") to single feature (called it "I_24_dissolve_back"), This ensures that the parent line actually has a vertex at each point.
  2. Split Lines ("I_24_dissolve_back") at Vertices on feature_diss; output is "I_24_segments_at_vertices"
  3. In the I_24_segments_at_vertices's attribute table, create a new field to store a copy of the FID. Calculate it as such
  4. Split Lines ("I_24_cut_by_county") at points ("I_24_points_at_line"), note that, Search Radius should be the segement length such as 0.1 mile. The output layer is "I_24_segments_at_points"
  5. Spatial Join "I_24_segments_at_vertices" to "I_24_segments_at_points", *average* the fields from "I_24_segments_at_vertices" in the output table. Label the output layer as "I_24_seg_spatial_join" *this step is also for ordering the segments by id of I_24_segments_at_vertices* After this step, we can delete some useless/duplicate columns (fields) to make the table more brief. Importantly, the semgent sequence can be determined by the Avg_copy_id, which will be further used to add the beg/end logmiles for segments.
  6. A little tip here, we can recalculate the length and check if they (marjority of them) are equal to 0.1

Retrieve segments.\

Copy Id. \

Split lines at points\

Order segments\

The final table should contain below information for further calculation

Add beg/end log miles to segments.¶

It is not easy to add beg/end log miles in the Arcmap table becasue we need to loop all sections in crossed counties. The best way I thought is to export the dataframe to excel (or dbf file), and use python to do it. Anyway, it might be possible of using arcpy package.
